			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Just curious exactly what you consider interferring as opposed to &quot;playing the game&quot;.  Here's an example.  Guildmate and I are in Nektulos hunting Dark Elf guards one night (hey, I'm a Halfling Druid, they had it coming!) when we hear summons from someone, requesting help for Innoruk.  Being overly curious and a bit mischievous, we go invisible, run up to Neriak and there is a GM event underway, with a GM recruiting baddies to serrve the will of Innoruk.  We could stand aside and ignore, or we could, as we did, sneak up behind him and proceed to berate him, taunt his gods and the fate of his people, sing the praises of our own deities, etc.<BR>
<BR>
By keeping everything in /say, he was aware that we were right there.  He responded in kind several times, threatening us, branding us cowards, etc.  We did this for about 20 minutes, bashing him and all who decided to listen to him, but all in game and context,  While the Gm played along, as did several others, we also got our fair share of flames too.<BR>
<BR>
To us, it was fun and a good in game experience, even though there was nothing more than the thrill of 2 characters under lvl20 standing feet behind the Neriak guards and coming up with good taunts.  But after reading the post, I was wondering if this qualified as us interferring with a GM event we weren't part of.  Just curious.<BR>
<BR>
Hooptie &lt;Faded Remnant&gt;<BR>
The Nameless
